, Tuong, Min, Tam, Tanh, Thai, Tham, Tinh, Yeong.  Chinese Hong, Hang, Sang, Tong, Chan, Chi, Hwa Ja, Hyung, Kam, Ki Bong, Kin, Man.","Vietnamese: from the Chinese surname 羅, see   Luo   1.","Vietnamese (<b>Lã</b>): from the Chinese surname 呂, see   Lu   6 and 3 below."],"variants":[{"name":"Luo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Wei, Jian, Yi, Ping, Yong, Zhen, Feng, Hong, Ming, Jin, Bin, Chen, Hai, Lan, Min, Huan, Hung, Shen, Tian.","Chinese:","Mandarin form of the surname 羅, meaning ‘net for catching birds’ or ‘to collect’ in Chinese: (i) from Luo (羅), the name of an ancient state (located in present-day Hubei province). After it was annexed by the state of Chu during the early Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ), people from the state migrated southwards and adopted Luo (羅) as their surname. (ii) from the Po Duo Luo (破多羅) and Chi Luo (叱羅) families from the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China, who changed their original surnames to 羅 during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ). (iii) from the personal name Hu Se Luo (斛瑟羅), leader of an ancient Turkic tribe who are believed to have migrated to China during the Tang dynasty (618–907  AD ). His descendants inherited his name Hu Se Luo (斛瑟羅) as their surname and shortened it to 羅 during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ). (iv) from the name of one of the seven families from the Bandun Man, an ethnic group residing in ancient southwestern China (located mainly in present-day Sichuan province)."]}]},{"name":"Guillaume","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>William</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"William","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."]}]},{"name":"II","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Loving’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Guillaume II de La Lande-Patry was born in 1065, in La Lande-Patry, Orne, Normandy, France as the son of Raoul I de La Lande-Patry and Mathilde. He married Mathilde DE LA ROCHE-TESSON about 1085, in Europe. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died on 15 May 1141, in his hometown, at the age of 76."},"et":{"1065–15 mai 1141":"1065–15. mai 1141","1065–1141":"1065–1141","1045–Female":"1045–Surnud","1085–Male":"1085–Surnud","1050–1096":"1050–1096","–Female":"Surnud","about 1085":"umbes 1085","1045":"1045","1065":"1065","before 1065":"enne 1065","1141":"1141","1085":"1085","1096":"1096","1050":"1050","15 mai 1141":"15. mai 1141","Europe":"Europe","La Lande-Patry, Orne, Normandie, France":"La Lande-Patry, Orne, Normandie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1065–15 mai 1141":"1065–15. toukokuuta 1141","1065–1141":"1065–1141","1045–Female":"1045–Kuollut","1085–Male":"1085–Kuollut","1050–1096":"1050–1096","–Female":"Kuollut","about 1085":"noin 1085","1045":"1045","1065":"1065","before 1065":"ennen vuotta 1065","1141":"1141","1085":"1085","1096":"1096","1050":"1050","15 mai 1141":"15. toukokuuta 1141","Europe":"Europe","La Lande-Patry, Orne, Normandie, France":"La Lande-Patry, Orne, Normandie, Ranska"},"fr":{"1065–15 mai 1141":"1065–15 mai 1141","1065–1141":"1065–1141","1045–Female":"1045–Décédée","1085–Male":"1085–Décédé","1050–1096":"1050–1096","–Female":"Décédée","about 1085":"environ 1085","1045":"1045","1065":"1065","before 1065":"avant 1065","1141":"1141","1085":"